          <h1>Postcards from Abroad</h1>
      <p>Each semester, students pack their bags then head to the airport, passport in hand.</p>

      <p>Through <a href="http://piratesabroad.ecu.edu/" target="_blank">Pirates Abroad</a>, students can live and receive their education abroad for an academic year, semester or summer. There are more than 200 programs in 50-plus countries. During the 2017-18 academic year, 702 students participated in curricular and co-curricular activities abroad.</p>

      <blockquote><p><span>“</span>Studying abroad gives students the opportunity to embrace other cultures, other perspectives, careers, competence while working with others. They gain a degree of confidence that they wouldn’t always have.<span>”</span>
      <cite>–Dr. Jon Rezek, assistant vice chancellor, Global Affairs</cite></p></blockquote>

      <p>This summer, 53 students enrolled in the ECU Tuscany program and lived in Certaldo Alto, Italy; 20 College of Business students explored business and culture in Alpine Europe; nine students in the science education graduate program used Costa Rica as a living-learning lab; 11 maritime studies graduate students conducted archaeological surveys of waters surrounding Saipan to locate and document sites related to World War II; and 10 students majoring in health and communication disciplines learned about health communication in Switzerland, where the Red Cross began in 1863. Here are their stories.</p>
